<!-- usually 10, 11 or 12-->\n }}\n}}\n\n'''Skegness Academy''' is a [[Mixed-sex education|coeducational]] [[secondary school]] and [[sixth form]] with [[Academy (English school)|academy status]], in [[Skegness]], [[Lincolnshire]], England.\n\n==History==\nLincolnshire has persisted in operating [[eleven plus|selection]] so the top 25% of the ability range is taken by [[Skegness Grammar School]] and others go elsewhere. In Skegness there are just two secondary schools.\nThe other school was the '''The Skegness Earl of Scarbrough High School'''<ref name=\"GIAS Earl\">{{cite web |title=The Skegness Earl of Scarbrough High School - GOV.UK |url=https://get-information-schools.service.gov.uk/Establishments/Establishment/Details/120656 |website=get-information-schools.service.gov.uk |accessdate=11 March 2020 |language=en}}</ref> until 2004 when it was closed, and reopened as '''St Clements College'''.<ref name=\"Clements\">{{cite web |title=St Clements College Review |url=https://www.skegness-attractions.co.uk/st-clements-college-review.html |website=Skegness Attractions |accessdate=11 March 2020 |date=6 March 2013}}</ref>\n\nThis 'fresh start' school converted to academy status in 2010, being one of the first academy schools in England, and was renamed '''Skegness Academy'''. The Skegness Academy is part of the [[Greenwood Academies Trust]] .  <!-- As of 1 February, Wayne Norrie (CEO of [[Greenwood Academies Trust]]) wrote to all parents informing them Skegness Academy was to be dropped from their portfolio of academies.  The new sponsor was not announced.  ...   Interesting story but needs a reference-->\n\nIn 2017 Skegness Academy was found 'inadequate' by [[Ofsted]] <ref name=\"Ofsted Report 2017\">{{cite web |title=Ofsted Report 2017 |url=https://files.ofsted.gov.uk/v1/file/2709269 |website=ofsted.gov.uk |accessdate=11 March 2020}}</ref> but has 'ambitious plan for improvement'. Skegness Academy has since been monitored closely by Ofsted.<ref name=\"Ofsted Monitoring Letter\">{{cite web |title=Special measures monitoring inspection of Skegness Academy January 2019 |url=https://files.ofsted.gov.uk/v1/file/50051740 |website=ofsted.gov.uk |accessdate=11 March 2020 |date=January 2019}}</ref>\n\nIn January 2020, Ofsted did a full inspection and acknowledged that the improvements had been put in place, but would take time to show effect. As a result, the school was removed from special measures as is now rated as 'requiring improvement'.<ref name=\"Ofsted Report 2020\">{{cite web |title=Ofsted Report 2020 |url=https://files.ofsted.gov.uk/v1/file/50144851 |website=ofsted.gov.uk |accessdate=11 March 2020}}</ref>\n\n==Curriculum==\nA higher proportion than average enter the school with attainment that is significantly below the national average need support to  effectively to develop literacy and numeracy skills.<ref name=\"Ofsted Report 2019\">{{cite web |title=Ofsted Report 2019 |url=https://files.ofsted.gov.uk/v1/file/50142705 |website=ofsted.gov.uk |accessdate=12 March 2020}}</ref>\n\nDuring Key Stage 3, pupils are taught English, mathematics, science, geography, history, RE, modern foreign languages, ICT, technology (including food technology), expressive arts (music, drama), art and PE. Key Stage 3 includes years 7, 8, and 9. Twenty minutes a day is devoted to a recreational reading session (Drop Everything and Read).<ref name=\"curriculum\">{{cite web |title=Skegness Academy - Curriculum |url=https://www.skegnessacademy.org/page/?title=Curriculum&pid=92 |website=www.skegnessacademy.org |accessdate=12 March 2020}}</ref>\n\nIn years 10 and 11, pupils choose four subjects to go with the core subjects Maths, English, Science, in either Level 2 BTEC or GCSE format, and PE.<ref name=\"curriculum\"/>\n\n===Pathways===\nAt Sixth Form three pathways are offered, students can take the Academic Pathway with A-Levels for university entry, the Core  Level 3 pathway which includes Level 3 BTECs and can also retake GCSE Maths and English if they have not achieved a Level 4 grade or above at Year 11. There is a Level 2 pathway offering vocational courses <ref name=\"Sixth Form Prospectus 2020\">{{cite web |title=Sixth Form Prospectus 2020 |url=https://www.skegnessacademy.org/_site/data/files/users/6/files/E9F3F6E58F8E08B23DE0D1AE2ED00FAA.pdf |website=www.skegnessacademy.org |accessdate=11 March 2020}}</ref>\n\nThe Sixth Form has a 100% pass rate across all Level 3 courses.<ref>http://www.lincolnshireecho.co.uk/Level-results-Skegness-Academy-achieve-100-cent/story-22730383-detail/story.html</ref>\n\n===Extra curricular activities (ECA)===\nExtra curricular activities are no longer something that teachers offer to share their enthusiasm but now activities that students are expected to engage in. There are the usual range of catch-up classes, and sports  music and dance activities that are in a coordinated schedule.<ref name=\"ECA\">{{cite web |title=ECAs at Skegness Academy |url=https://www.skegnessacademy.org/_site/data/files/documents/E88BB4D74492B27C746ECB37521E8989.pdf |website=www.skegnessacademy.org |accessdate=11 March 2020}}</ref> As part of the process to address the Ofsted judgement, students have been consulted and the following activities are being considered:Hair and beauty, \nAdvanced dancing, Gliding, Rock climbing, First aid, Swimming, Skate park/roller skating, Gymnastics, Cheer leading.<ref name=\"ECA\"/>\n\n== References ==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n== External links ==\n* {{Official website|http://www.skegnessacademy.org/|Skegness Academy official website}}\n\n{{Schools in Lincolnshire}}\n\n[[Category:Secondary schools in Lincolnshire]]\n[[Category:Academies in Lincolnshire]]\n[[Category:Skegness]]\n\n\n{{Lincolnshire-school-stub}}\n", "text_old": "{{Use dmy dates|date=January 2015}}\n{{Use British English|date=January 2015}}\n{{Infobox UK school \n| name          = Skegness Academy\n| image         =\n| image_size          = \n| logo   =  File:Fair use logo Skegness Academy.png\n| coordinates   = 