eleven plus|selection]] so the top 25% of the ability range is taken by [[Skegness Grammar School]] and others go elsewhere. In Skegness there are just two secondary schools.\nThe other school was the '''The Skegness Earl of Scarbrough High School'''<ref name=\"GIAS Earl\">{{cite web |title=The Skegness Earl of Scarbrough High School - GOV.UK |url=https://get-information-schools.service.gov.uk/Establishments/Establishment/Details/120656 |website=get-information-schools.service.gov.uk |accessdate=11 March 2020 |language=en}}</ref> until 2004 when it was closed, and reopened as '''St Clements College'''.<ref name=\"Clements\">{{cite web |title=St Clements College Review |url=https://www.skegness-attractions.co.uk/st-clements-college-review.html |website=Skegness Attractions |accessdate=11 March 2020 |date=6 March 2013}}</ref>\n\nThis 'fresh start' school converted to academy status in 2010, being one of the first academy schools in England, and was renamed '''Skegness Academy'''. The Skegness Academy is part of the [[Greenwood Academies Trust]] .  <!-- As of 1 February, Wayne Norrie (CEO of [[Greenwood Academies Trust]]) wrote to all parents informing them Skegness Academy was to be dropped from their portfolio of academies.  The new sponsor was not announced.  ...   Interesting story but needs a reference-->\n\nIn 2017 Skegness Academy was found 'inadequate' by [[Ofsted]] <ref name=\"Ofsted Report 2017\">{{cite web |title=Ofsted Report 2017 |url=https://files.ofsted.gov.uk/v1/file/2709269 |website=ofsted.gov.uk |accessdate=11 March 2020}}</ref> but has 'ambitious plan for improvement'. Skegness Academy has since been monitored closely by Ofsted.<ref name=\"Ofsted Monitoring Letter\">{{cite web |title=Special measures monitoring inspection of Skegness Academy January 2019 |url=https://files.ofsted.gov.uk/v1/file/50051740 |website=ofsted.gov.uk |accessdate=11 March 2020 |date=January 2019}}</ref>\n\nIn January 2020, Ofsted did a full inspection and acknowledged that the improvements had been put in place, but would take time to show effect. As a result, the school was removed from special measures as is now rated as 'requiring improvement'.<ref name=\"Ofsted Report 2020\">{{cite web |title=Ofsted Report 2020 |url=https://files.ofsted.gov.uk/v1/file/50144851 |website=ofsted.gov.uk |accessdate=11 March 2020}}</ref>\n\n==Curriculum==\nA higher proportion than average enter the school with attainment that is significantly below the national average need support to  effectively to develop literacy and numeracy skills.<ref name=\"Ofsted Report 2019\">{{cite web |title=Ofsted Report 2019 |url=https://files.ofsted.gov.uk/v1/file/50142705 |website=ofsted.gov.uk |accessdate=12 March 2020}}</ref>\n\nDuring Key Stage 3, pupils are taught English, mathematics, science, geography, history, RE, modern foreign languages, ICT, technology (including food technology), expressive arts (music, drama), art and PE. Key Stage 3 includes years 7, 8 ,and 9. Twenty minutes a day is devoted to a recreational reading session (Drop Everything and Read).<ref name=\"curriculum\">{{cite web |title=Skegness Academy - Curriculum |url=https://www.skegnessacademy.org/page/?title=Curriculum&pid=92 |website=www.skegnessacademy.org |accessdate=12 March 2020}}</ref>\n\nIn years 10 and 11, pupils choose four subjects to go with the core subjects Maths, English, Science, in either Level 2 BTEC or GCSE format, and PE.<ref name=\"curriculum\"/>\n\n===Pathways===\nAt Sixth Form three pathways are offered , students can take the Academic Pathway with A-Levels for university entry, the Core  Level 3 pathway which includes Level 3 BTECs and can also retake GCSE Maths and English if they have not achieved a Level 4 grade or above at Year 11. There is a Level 2 pathway offering vocational courses <ref name=\"Sixth Form Prospectus 2020\">{{cite web |title=Sixth Form Prospectus 2020 |url=https://www.skegnessacademy.org/_site/data/files/users/6/files/E9F3F6E58F8E08B23DE0D1AE2ED00FAA.pdf |website=www.skegnessacademy.org |accessdate=11 March 2020}}</ref>\n\nThe Sixth Form has a 100% pass rate across all Level 3 courses.<ref>http://www.lincolnshireecho.co.uk/Level-results-Skegness-Academy-achieve-100-cent/story-22730383-detail/story.html</ref>\n\n===Extra curricular activities (ECA)===\nExtra curricular activites are no longer something that teachers offer to share their enthusiasm but now activities that students are expected to engage in. There are the usual range of catch-up classes, and sports  music and dance activities that are in a coordinated schedule.<ref name=\"ECA\">{{cite web |title=ECAs at Skegness Academy |url=https://www.skegnessacademy.org/_site/data/files/documents/E88BB4D74492B27C746ECB37521E8989.pdf |website=www.skegnessacademy.org |accessdate=11 March 2020}}</ref> As part of the process to address the Ofsted judgement, students have been consulted and the following activies are being considered:Hair and beauty, \nAdvanced dancing, Gliding, Rock climbing, First aid, Swimming, Skate park/roller skating, Gymnastics, Cheer leading.<ref name=\"ECA\"/>\n\n== References ==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n== External links ==\n* {{Official website|http://www.skegnessacademy.org/|Skegness Academy official website}}\n\n{{Schools in Lincolnshire}}\n\n[[Category:Secondary schools in Lincolnshire]]\n[[Category:Academies in Lincolnshire]]\n[[Category:Skegness]]\n\n\n{{Lincolnshire-school-stub}}\n", "name_user": "Nat965", "label": "safe", "comment": "ApplyGen fix(es),typo(s) fixed: activites \u2192 activities,  , \u2192 ,  (2), activies \u2192 activities", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Skegness_Academy"}
{"title_page": "Temafloxacin", "text_new": "{{short description|Chemical compound, antibiotic drug}}\n{{Drugbox\n| Verifiedfields = changed\n| Watchedfields = changed\n| verifiedrevid = 416705224\n| IUPAC_name = 1-(2,4-Difluorophenyl)-6-fluoro-7-(3-methylpiperazin-1-yl)-4-oxoquinoline-3-carboxylic acid\n| image = Temafloxacin.png\n\n<!--Clinical data-->\n| tradename = Omniflox\n| pregnancy_AU = <!-- A / B1 / B2 / B3 / C / D / X -->\n| pregnancy_US = <!-- A / B            / C / D / X -->\n| legal_AU = <!-- Unscheduled / S2 / S3 / S4 / S5 / S6 / S7 / S8 / S9 -->\n| legal_CA = <!--             / Schedule I, II, III, IV, V, VI, VII, VIII -->\n| legal_UK = <!-- GSL         / P       / POM / CD / Class A, B, C -->\n| legal_US = <!-- OTC                   / Rx-only  / Schedule I, II, III, IV, V -->\n| legal_status = Withdrawn\n| routes_of_administration = Oral\n\n<!--Identifiers-->\n| CAS_number_Ref = {{cascite|correct|CAS}}\n| CAS_number = 108319-06-8\n| ATC_prefix = J01\n| ATC_suffix = MA05\n| PubChem = 60021\n| DrugBank_Ref = {{drugbankcite|changed|drugbank}}\n| DrugBank = DB01405\n| ChemSpiderID_Ref = {{chemspidercite|correct|chemspider}}\n| ChemSpiderID = 54143\n| UNII_Ref = {{fdacite|correct|FDA}}\n| UNII = 1WZ12GTT67\n| KEGG_Ref = {{keggcite|changed|kegg}}\n| KEGG = D02469\n| ChEBI_Ref = {{ebicite|changed|EBI}} \n| ChEBI = 77788\n| ChEMBL_Ref = {{ebicite|correct|EBI}}\n| ChEMBL = 277100\n\n<!--Chemical data-->\n| C=21 | H=18 | F=3 | N=3 | O=3 \n| molecular_weight = 417.381 g/mol\n| smiles = Fc1ccc(c(F)c1)N\\3c2cc(c(F)cc2C(=O)C(/C(=O)O)=C/3)N4CC(NCC4)C\n| StdInChI_Ref = {{stdinchicite|correct|chemspider}}\n| StdInChI = 1S/C21H18F3N3O3/c1-11-9-26(5-4-25-11)19-8-18-13(7-16(19)24)20(28)14(21(29)30)10-27(18)17-3-2-12(22)6-15(17)23/h2-3,6-8,10-11,25H,4-5,9H2,1H3,(H,29,30)\n| StdInChIKey_Ref = {{stdinchicite|correct|chemspider}}\n| StdInChIKey = QKDHBVNJCZBTMR-UHFFFAOYSA-N\n}}\n\n'''Temafloxacin''' (marketed by [[Abbott Laboratories]] as '''Omniflox''') is a [[fluoroquinolone]] [[antibiotic]] drug which was withdrawn from sale in the [[United States]] shortly after its approval in 1992 because of serious [[adverse effect]]s resulting in three deaths.<ref name=\"urlwww.fda.gov\">{{cite web |url=https://www.fda.gov/ohrms/dockets/ac/98/briefingbook/1998-3454B1_03_WL49.pdf |title=Recalling the Omniflox (Temafloxacin) Tablets |format= pdf |work= Food and Drug Administration |date= 1992-06-05 |accessdate=2014-10-15}}</ref><ref name=\"ABBOTT WITHDRAWS TEMAFLOXACIN\">{{cite web |title=ABBOTT WITHDRAWS TEMAFLOXACIN - Pharmaceutical industry news |work= The Pharmaletter |date= 1992-06-15 |url=http://www.thepharmaletter.com/article/abbott-withdraws-temafloxacin  |accessdate=2014-10-16}}</ref> It is not marketed in Europe.\n\n== History ==\nOmniflox was approved to treat lower respiratory tract infections, genital and urinary infections like prostatitis, and skin infections in the United States by the [[Food and Drug Administration]] in January 1992. Severe adverse reactions, including [[allergic reaction]]s and [[hemolytic anemia]],<ref>{{Cite journal|title=History of quinolones and their side effects.|journal=Chemotherapy|volume=47 Suppl 3|issue=|pages=3\u20138; discussion 44\u20138|doi=10.1159/000057838|pmid=11549783|last1=Rubinstein|first1=E.}}</ref> developed in over 100 patients during the first four months of its use, leading to three patient deaths. Abbott withdrew the drug from sale in June 1992.\n\n== Pharmacokinetics ==\nFollowing oral administration the compound is well absorbed from the [[gastrointestinal tract]]. The oral [[bioavailability]] is greater than 90%. Temafloxacin has a good tissue penetration in various [[biological fluids]] and [[biological tissues|tissues]], particularly in the respiratory tissues, nasal secretions, [[tonsils]], [[prostate]] and [[Bone marrow|bone]].<ref name=\"pmid1662896\">{{cite journal |vauthors=Sorgel F, Naber KG, Kinzig M, Mahr G, Muth P |title=Comparative pharmacokinetics of ciprofloxacin and temafloxacin in humans: a review |journal=Am. J. Med. |volume=91 |issue=6A |pages=51S\u201366S |date=December 1991  |pmid=1662896 |doi= 10.1016/0002-9343(91)90312-L }}</ref> In these districts the concentrations achieved are equal to or higher than those in serum.<ref name=\"pmid1319872\">{{cite journal |author=S\u00f6rgel F |title=Penetration of temafloxacin into body tissues and fluids |journal=Clin Pharmacokinet |volume=22 Suppl 1 |issue= |pages=57\u201363 |year=1992 |pmid=1319872 |doi= 10.2165/00003088-199200221-00010|url= }}</ref> The fluoroquinolone has a 7-8 hour [[Half-life, biological|half-life]].<ref name=\"pmid1662889\">{{cite journal |author=Pankey GA |title=Temafloxacin: an overview |journal=Am. J. Med. |volume=91 |issue=6A |pages=166S\u2013172S |date=December 1991  |pmid=1662889 |doi= 10.1016/0002-9343(91)90332-r }}</ref>\nThe penetration into the [[central nervous system]] (CNS)is less pronounced.<ref name=\"pmid1662889\"/> The excretion from the body is primarily due to glomerular filtration in the kidneys.<ref name=\"pmid1318680\">{{cite journal |vauthors=Granneman GR, Carpentier P, Morrison PJ, Pernet AG |title=Pharmacokinetics of temafloxacin in humans after multiple oral doses |journal=Antimicrob. Agents Chemother. |volume=36 |issue=2 |pages=378\u201386 |date=February 1992  |pmid=1318680 |pmc=188445 |doi= 10.1128/aac.36.2.378|url=http://aac.asm.org/cgi/pmidlookup?view=long&pmid=1318680 |accessdate=2014-10-17}}</ref><ref name=\"pmid1666497\">{{cite journal |vauthors=Granneman GR, Braeckman R, Kraut J, Shupien S, Craft JC |title=Temafloxacin pharmacokinetics in subjects with normal and impaired renal function |journal=Antimicrob. Agents Chemother. |volume=35 |issue=11 |pages=2345\u201351 |date=November 1991  |pmid=1666497 |pmc=245383 |doi= 10.1128/aac.35.11.2345|url=http://aac.asm.org/cgi/pmidlookup?view=long&pmid=1666497 |accessdate=2014-10-17}}</ref><ref name=\"pmid1664830\">{{cite journal |author=Dudley MN |title=A review of the pharmacokinetic profile of temafloxacin |journal=J. Antimicrob. Chemother. |volume=28 Suppl C |issue= |pages=55\u201364 |date=December 1991  |pmid=1664830 |doi= 10.1093/jac/28.suppl_c.55|url=http://jac.oxfordjournals.org/cgi/pmidlookup?view=long&pmid=1664830 |accessdate=2014-10-17}}</ref>\n\n== Clinical uses ==\nThe compound was indicated for treating lower respiratory tract infections ([[community-acquired pneumonia]], exacerbations of [[Bronchitis#Chronic bronchitis|chronic bronchitis]]), genital and [[urinary tract]] infections ([[prostatitis]], [[Gonococcal urethritis|gonococcal]] and [[non-gonococcal urethritis]], [[cervicitis]]), [[Skin infection|skin]] and [[soft tissue]] infections.<ref name=\"pmid1662889\"/><ref name=\"pmid1787128\">{{cite journal |author=Gentry LO |title=Review of quinolones in the treatment of infections of the skin and skin structure |journal=J. Antimicrob. Chemother. |volume=28 Suppl C |issue= |pages=97\u2013110 |date=December 1991  |pmid=1787128 |doi= 10.1093/jac/28.suppl_C.97|url=http://jac.oxfordjournals.org/cgi/pmidlookup?view=long&pmid=1787128 |accessdate=2014-10-17}}</ref><ref name=\"pmid1662897\">{{cite journal |author=Wise R |title=Comparative penetration of selected fluoroquinolones into respiratory tract fluids and tissues |journal=Am. J. Med. |volume=91 |issue=6A |pages=67S\u201370S |date=December 1991  |pmid=1662897 |doi= 10.1016/0002-9343(91)90313-M}}</ref><ref name=\"pmid1325892\">{{cite journal |vauthors=Symonds WT, Nix DE |title=Lomefloxacin and temafloxacin: two new fluoroquinolone antimicrobials |journal=Clin Pharm |volume=11 |issue=9 |pages=753\u201366 |date=September 1992  |pmid=1325892 |doi= |url= }}</ref>\n\n==See also==\n* [[Quinolones]]\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n* [https://www.fda.gov/ohrms/dockets/ac/98/briefingbook/1998-3454B1_03_WL49.pdf FDA press release] June 5, 1992.\n\n{{QuinoloneAntiBiotics}}\n\n[[Category:Fluoroquinolone antibiotics]]\n[[Category:Hepatotoxins]]\n[[Category:Withdrawn drugs]]\n[[Category:AbbVie Inc. brands]]\n[[Category:1,4-di-hydro-7-(1-piperazinyl)-4-oxo-3-quinolinecarboxylic acids]]\n", "text_old": "{{short description|Chemical compound, antibiotic drug}}\n{{Drugbox\n| Verifiedfields = changed\n| Watchedfields = changed\n| verifiedrevid = 416705224\n| IUPAC_name = 1-(2,4-Difluorophenyl)-6-fluoro-7-(3-methylpiperazin-1-yl)-4-oxoquinoline-3-carboxylic acid\n| image = Temafloxacin.png\n\n<!--Clinical data-->\n| tradename = Omniflox\n| pregnancy_AU = <!-- A / B1 / B2 / B3 / C / D / X -->\n| pregnancy_US = <!-- A / B            / C / D / X -->\n| legal_AU = <!-- Unscheduled / S2 / S3 / S4 / S5 / S6 / S7 / S8 / S9 -->\n| legal_CA = <!--             / Schedule I, II, III, IV, V, VI, VII, VIII -->\n| legal_UK = <!-- GSL         / P       / POM / CD / Class A, B, C -->\n| legal_US = <!-- OTC                   / Rx-only  / Schedule I, II, III, IV, V -->\n| legal_status = Withdrawn\n| routes_of_administration = Oral\n\n<!--Identifiers-->\n| ATC_prefix = J01\n| ATC_suffix = MA05\n| PubChem = 60021\n| DrugBank_Ref = {{drugbankcite|changed|drugbank}}\n| DrugBank = DB01405\n| ChemSpiderID_Ref = {{chemspidercite|correct|chemspider}}\n| ChemSpiderID = 54143\n| UNII_Ref = {{fdacite|changed|FDA}}\n| UNII = 1WZ12GTT67\n| KEGG_Ref = {{keggcite|changed|kegg}}\n| KEGG = D02469\n| ChEBI_Ref = {{ebicite|changed|EBI}} \n| ChEBI = 77788\n| ChEMBL_Ref = {{ebicite|correct|EBI}}\n| ChEMBL = 277100\n\n<!--Chemical data-->\n| C=21 | H=18 | F=3 | N=3 | O=3 \n| molecular_weight = 417.381 g/mol\n| smiles = Fc1ccc(c(F)c1)N\\3c2cc(c(F)cc2C(=O)C(/C(=O)O)=C/3)N4CC(NCC4)C\n| StdInChI_Ref = {{stdinchicite|correct|chemspider}}\n| StdInChI = 1S/C21H18F3N3O3/c1-11-9-26(5-4-25-11)19-8-18-13(7-16(19)24)20(28)14(21(29)30)10-27(18)17-3-2-12(22)6-15(17)23/h2-3,6-8,10-11,25H,4-5,9H2,1H3,(H,29,30)\n| StdInChIKey_Ref = {{stdinchicite|correct|chemspider}}\n| StdInChIKey = QKDHBVNJCZBTMR-UHFFFAOYSA-N\n}}\n\n'''Temafloxacin''' (marketed by [[Abbott Laboratories]] as '''Omniflox''') is a [[fluoroquinolone]] [[antibiotic]] drug which was withdrawn from sale in the [[United States]] shortly after its approval in 1992 because of serious [[adverse effect]]s resulting in three deaths.<ref name=\"urlwww.fda.gov\">{{cite web |url=https://www.fda.gov/ohrms/dockets/ac/98/briefingbook/1998-3454B1_03_WL49.pdf |title=Recalling the Omniflox (Temafloxacin) Tablets |format= pdf |work= Food and Drug Administration |date= 1992-06-05 |accessdate=2014-10-15}}</ref><ref name=\"ABBOTT WITHDRAWS TEMAFLOXACIN\">{{cite web |title=ABBOTT WITHDRAWS TEMAFLOXACIN - Pharmaceutical industry news |work= The Pharmaletter |date= 1992-06-15 |url=http://www.thepharmaletter.com/article/abbott-withdraws-temafloxacin  |accessdate=2014-10-16}}</ref> It is not marketed in Europe.\n\n== History ==\nOmniflox was approved to treat lower respiratory tract infections, genital and urinary infections like prostatitis, and skin infections in the United States by the [[Food and Drug Administration]] in January 1992. Severe adverse reactions, including [[allergic reaction]]s and [[hemolytic anemia]],<ref>{{Cite journal|title=History of quinolones and their side effects.|journal=Chemotherapy|volume=47 Suppl 3|issue=|pages=3\u20138; discussion 44\u20138|doi=10.1159/000057838|pmid=11549783|last1=Rubinstein|first1=E.}}</ref> developed in over 100 patients during the first four months of its use, leading to three patient deaths. Abbott withdrew the drug from sale in June 1992.\n\n== Pharmacokinetics ==\nFollowing oral administration the compound is well absorbed from the [[gastrointestinal tract]]. The oral [[bioavailability]] is greater than 90%. Temafloxacin has a good tissue penetration in various [[biological fluids]] and [[biological tissues|tissues]], particularly in the respiratory tissues, nasal secretions, [[tonsils]], [[prostate]] and [[Bone marrow|bone]].<ref name=\"pmid1662896\">{{cite journal |vauthors=Sorgel F, Naber KG, Kinzig M, Mahr G, Muth P |title=Comparative pharmacokinetics of ciprofloxacin and temafloxacin in humans: a review |journal=Am. J. Med. |volume=91 |issue=6A |pages=51S\u201366S |date=December 1991  |pmid=1662896 |doi= 10.1016/0002-9343(91)90312-L }}</ref> In these districts the concentrations achieved are equal to or higher than those in serum.<ref name=\"pmid1319872\">{{cite journal |author=S\u00f6rgel F |title=Penetration of temafloxacin into body tissues and fluids |journal=Clin Pharmacokinet |volume=22 Suppl 1 |issue= |pages=57\u201363 |year=1992 |pmid=1319872 |doi= 10.2165/00003088-199200221-00010|url= }}</ref> The fluoroquinolone has a 7-8 hour [[Half-life, biological|half-life]].<ref name=\"pmid1662889\">{{cite journal |author=Pankey GA |title=Temafloxacin: an overview |journal=Am. J. Med. |volume=91 |issue=6A |pages=166S\u2013172S |date=December 1991  |pmid=1662889 |doi= 10.1016/0002-9343(91)90332-r }}</ref>\nThe penetration into the [[central nervous system]] (CNS)is less pronounced.<ref name=\"pmid1662889\"/> The excretion from the body is primarily due to glomerular filtration in the kidneys.<ref name=\"pmid1318680\">{{cite journal |vauthors=Granneman GR, Carpentier P, Morrison PJ, Pernet AG |title=Pharmacokinetics of temafloxacin in humans after multiple oral doses |journal=Antimicrob. Agents Chemother. |volume=36 |issue=2 |pages=378\u201386 |date=February 1992  |pmid=1318680 |pmc=188445 |doi= 10.1128/aac.36.2.378|url=http://aac.asm.org/cgi/pmidlookup?view=long&pmid=1318680 |accessdate=2014-10-17}}</ref><ref name=\"pmid1666497\">{{cite journal |vauthors=Granneman GR, Braeckman R, Kraut J, Shupien S, Craft JC |title=Temafloxacin pharmacokinetics in subjects with normal and impaired renal function |journal=Antimicrob. Agents Chemother. |volume=35 |issue=11 |pages=2345\u201351 |date=November 1991  |pmid=1666497 |pmc=245383 |doi= 10.1128/aac.35.11.2345|url=http://aac.asm.org/cgi/pmidlookup?view=long&pmid=1666497 |accessdate=2014-10-17}}</ref><ref name=\"pmid1664830\">{{cite journal |author=Dudley MN |title=A review of the pharmacokinetic profile of temafloxacin |journal=J. Antimicrob. Chemother. |volume=28 Suppl C |issue= |pages=55\u201364 |date=December 1991  |pmid=1664830 |doi= 10.1093/jac/28.suppl_c.55|url=http://jac.oxfordjournals.org/cgi/pmidlookup?view=long&pmid=1664830 |accessdate=2014-10-17}}</ref>\n\n== Clinical uses ==\nThe compound was indicated for treating lower respiratory tract infections ([[community-acquired pneumonia]], exacerbations of [[Bronchitis#Chronic bronchitis|chronic bronchitis]]), genital and [[urinary tract]] infections ([[prostatitis]], [[Gonococcal urethritis|gonococcal]] and [[non-gonococcal urethritis]], [[cervicitis]]), [[Skin infection|skin]] and [[soft tissue]] infections.<ref name=\"pmid1662889\"/><ref name=\"pmid1787128\">{{cite journal |author=Gentry LO |title=Review of quinolones in the treatment of infections of the skin and skin structure |journal=J. Antimicrob. Chemother. |volume=28 Suppl C |issue= |pages=97\u2013110 |date=December 1991  |pmid=1787128 |doi= 10.1093/jac/28.suppl_C.97|url=http://jac.oxfordjournals.org/cgi/pmidlookup?view=long&pmid=1787128 |accessdate=2014-10-17}}</ref><ref name=\"pmid1662897\">{{cite journal |author=Wise R |title=Comparative penetration of selected fluoroquinolones into respiratory tract fluids and tissues |journal=Am. J. Med. |volume=91 |issue=6A |pages=67S\u201370S |date=December 1991  |pmid=1662897 |doi= 10.1016/0002-9343(91)90313-M}}</ref><ref name=\"pmid1325892\">{{cite journal |vauthors=Symonds WT, Nix DE |title=Lomefloxacin and temafloxacin: two new fluoroquinolone antimicrobials |journal=Clin Pharm |volume=11 |issue=9 |pages=753\u201366 |date=September 1992  |pmid=1325892 |doi= |url= }}</ref>\n\n==See also==\n* [[Quinolones]]\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n* [https://www.fda.gov/ohrms/dockets/ac/98/briefingbook/1998-3454B1_03_WL49.pdf FDA press release] June 5, 1992.\n\n{{QuinoloneAntiBiotics}}\n\n[[Category:Fluoroquinolone antibiotics]]\n[[Category:Hepatotoxins]]\n[[Category:Withdrawn drugs]]\n[[Category:AbbVie Inc. brands]]\n[[Category:1,4-di-hydro-7-(1-piperazinyl)-4-oxo-3-quinolinecarboxylic acids]]\n", "name_user": "Fswitzer4", "label": "safe", "comment": "Added CAS", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Temafloxacin"}
{"title_page": "Electronic organizer", "text_new": "{{refimprove|date=January 2020}}\nAn '''electronic organizer''' (or '''electric organizer''') is a small [[calculator]]-sized computer, often with an built-in [[diary]] application and other functions such as an address book and calendar.  It normally has a small [[alphanumeric]] keypad and an [[liquid crystal display|LCD]] screen of one, two, or three lines. The electronic diary or organizer was invented by an Indian businessman [[Sam Pitroda|Satyan Pitroda]] in 1975. He is regarded as one of the earliest pioneers of hand-held computing because of his invention of the Electronic Diary in 1975.<ref>https://www.computerhistory.org/revolution/mobile-computing/18/318/1716</ref>\n[[Image:SharpElectronicOrganiser-open.jpg|right|thumb|250px|Opened Sharp Electric Organizer model (sold as Sharp Wizard in the US) model ZQ-770.]]\n[[Image:Casio Digital Diary SF-R20 open.JPG|right|thumb|Casio SF-R20 Digital Diary featuring 256KB RAM, from around 1993.]]\n[[Image:BN-40A 2.JPG|right|thumb|Casio Business Navigator BN-40A.]]\n\nThey were very popular especially with businessmen during the 1990s, but because of the advent of [[personal digital assistants]], and later [[smartphones]] in the 2000s and 2010s respectively, both of which have a larger set of features, electronic organizers are mostly seen today for research purposes. One of the leading research topics being the study of how electronics can help people with mental disabilities use this type of equipment to aid their daily life.<ref>{{Cite journal|last=Bryen|first=Diane Nelson|last2=Carey|first2=Allison|last3=Friedman|first3=Mark|date=February 2007|title=Cell Phone Use by Adults With Intellectual Disabilities|journal=Intellectual and Developmental Disabilities|volume=45|issue=1|pages=1\u20132|doi=10.1352/1934-9556(2007)45[1:cpubaw]2.0.co;2|issn=1934-9491}}</ref>  Electronic organizers have more recently been used to support people with Alzheimer's disease to have a visual representation of a schedule.<ref>{{Cite journal|last=Imbeault|first=H\u00e9l\u00e8ne|last2=Pigot|first2=H\u00e9l\u00e8ne|last3=Bier|first3=Nathalie|last4=Gagnon|first4=Lise|last5=Marcotte|first5=Nicolas|last6=Giroux|first6=Sylvain|last7=F\u00fcl\u00fcp|first7=Tamas|date=2011|editor-last=Abdulrazak|editor-first=Bessam|editor2-last=Giroux|editor2-first=Sylvain|editor3-last=Bouchard|editor3-first=Bruno|editor4-last=Pigot|editor4-first=H\u00e9l\u00e8ne|editor5-last=Mokhtari|editor5-first=Mounir|title=Interdisciplinary Design of an Electronic Organizer for Persons with Alzheimer's Disease|journal=Toward Useful Services for Elderly and People with Disabilities|volume=6719|series=Lecture Notes in Computer Science|language=en|publisher=Springer Berlin Heidelberg|pages=137\u2013144|doi=10.1007/978-3-642-21535-3_18|isbn=978-3-642-21535-3}}</ref>\n\n==Casio digital diary==\nCasio digital diaries were produced by [[Casio]] in the early and mid 1990s, but have since been entirely superseded by Mobile Phones and PDAs.\n\n==Other electronic organizers ==\n\nWhile Casio was a major role player in the field of electronic organizers there were many different ideas, patent request, and manufacturers of the electronic organizers.<ref>{{Cite patent|title=Combination pager, organizer and radio|gdate=1997-06-13|url=https://patents.google.com/patent/US5929774A/en}}</ref> [[Rolodex]] who is namely known for their index card holders in the 1980s, [[Sharp Electronics]] who is mostly known for their printers and audio visual equipment, and lastly Royal electronics were all large contributors to the electronic organizer in its heyday.\n\n===Features===\n* Telephone directory\n* Schedule keeper: Keep track of appointments.\n* Memo function: Store text data such as price lists, airplane schedules, and more.\n* To do list: Keep track of daily tasks, checking off items as you complete them.\n* World time: Find out the current time in virtually any location on the globe.\n* Secret memory area: The secret memory area keeps personal data private. Once a password is registered, data is locked away until the password is used to access the secret area.\n* Alarm\n* Metric conversion function: Conversion between metric units and another measurement unit.\n* Currency conversion function\n* Game: Some machines included a game such as Poker or Blackjack.\n\n==See also==\n* [[Personal digital assistant|PDA]]\n* [[Smartphone]]\n* [[Pocket computer]]\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n{{Commons}}\n\n{{Computer sizes}}\n\n[[Category:Mobile computers]]\n\n\n{{compu-mobile-stub}}\n\n[[de:Electronic Organizer]]\n[[ja:\u96fb\u5b50\u624b\u5e33]]\n", "text_old": "{{refimprove|date=January 2020}}\nAn '''electronic organizer''' (or '''electric organizer''') is a small [[calculator]]-sized computer, often with an built-in [[diary]] application and other functions such as an address book and calendar.  It normally has a small [[alphanumeric]] keypad and an [[liquid crystal display|LCD]] screen of one, two, or three lines. The electronic diary or organizer was invented by an Indian businessman [[Sam Pitroda|Satyan Pitroda]] in 1975. He is regarded as one of the earliest pioneers of hand-held computing because of his invention of the Electronic Diary in 1975.<ref>https://www.computerhistory.org/revolution/mobile-computing/18/318/1716</ref>\n[[Image:SharpElectronicOrganiser-open.jpg|right|thumb|250px|Opened Sharp Electric Organizer model (sold as Sharp Wizard in the US) model ZQ-770.]]\n[[Image:Casio Digital Diary SF-R20 open.JPG|right|thumb|Casio SF-R20 Digital Diary featuring 256KB RAM, from around 1993.]]\n[[Image:BN-40A 2.JPG|right|thumb|Casio Business Navigator BN-40A.]]\n\nThey were very popular especially with businessmen during the 1990s, but because of the advent of [[personal digital assistants]], and later [[smartphones]] in the 2000s and 2010s respectively, both of which have a larger set of features, electronic organizers are mostly seen today for research purposes. One of the leading research topics being the study of how electronics can help people with mental disabilities use this type of equipment to aid their daily life.<ref>{{Cite journal|last=Bryen|first=Diane Nelson|last2=Carey|first2=Allison|last3=Friedman|first3=Mark|date=February 2007|title=Cell Phone Use by Adults With Intellectual Disabilities|journal=Intellectual and Developmental Disabilities|volume=45|issue=1|pages=1\u20132|doi=10.1352/1934-9556(2007)45[1:cpubaw]2.0.co;2|issn=1934-9491}}</ref>  Electronic organizers have more recently been used to support people with Alzheimer's disease to have a visual representation of a schedule.<ref>{{Cite journal|last=Imbeault|first=H\u00e9l\u00e8ne|last2=Pigot|first2=H\u00e9l\u00e8ne|last3=Bier|first3=Nathalie|last4=Gagnon|first4=Lise|last5=Marcotte|first5=Nicolas|last6=Giroux|first6=Sylvain|last7=F\u00fcl\u00fcp|first7=Tamas|date=2011|editor-last=Abdulrazak|editor-first=Bessam|editor2-last=Giroux|editor2-first=Sylvain|editor3-last=Bouchard|editor3-first=Bruno|editor4-last=Pigot|editor4-first=H\u00e9l\u00e8ne|editor5-last=Mokhtari|editor5-first=Mounir|title=Interdisciplinary Design of an Electronic Organizer for Persons with Alzheimer's Disease|journal=Toward Useful Services for Elderly and People with Disabilities|volume=6719|series=Lecture Notes in Computer Science|language=en|publisher=Springer Berlin Heidelberg|pages=137\u2013144|doi=10.1007/978-3-642-21535-3_18|isbn=978-3-642-21535-3}}</ref>\n\n==Casio digital diary==\nCasio digital diaries were produced by [[Casio]] in the early and mid 1990s, but have since been entirely superseded by Mobile Phones and PDAs.\n\n==Other electronic organizers ==\n\nWhile Casio was a major role player in the field of electronic organizers there were many different ideas, patent request, and manufacturers of the electronic organizers.<ref>{{Cite patent|title=Combination pager, organizer and radio|gdate=1997-06-13|url=https://patents.google.com/patent/US5929774A/en}}</ref> [[Rolodex]] who is namely known for their index card holders in the 1980's, [[Sharp Electronics]] who is mostly known for their printers and audio visual equipment, and lastly Royal electronics were all large contributors to the electronic organizer in its heyday.\n\n===Features===\n* Telephone directory\n* Schedule keeper: Keep track of appointments.\n* Memo function: Store text data such as price lists, airplane schedules, and more.\n* To do list: Keep track of daily tasks, checking off items as you complete them.\n* World time: Find out the current time in virtually any location on the globe.\n* Secret memory area: The secret memory area keeps personal data private. Once a password is registered, data is locked away until the password is used to access the secret area.\n* Alarm\n* Metric conversion function: Conversion between metric units and another measurement unit.\n* Currency conversion function\n* Game: Some machines included a game such as Poker or Blackjack.\n\n==See also==\n* [[Personal digital assistant|PDA]]\n* [[Smartphone]]\n* [[Pocket computer]]\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n{{Commons}}\n\n{{Computer sizes}}\n\n[[Category:Mobile computers]]\n\n\n{{compu-mobile-stub}}\n\n[[de:Electronic Organizer]]\n[[ja:\u96fb\u5b50\u624b\u5e33]]\n", "name_user": "Iridescent", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eOther electronic organizers:Cleanup andtypo fixing,typo(s) fixed: 1980's \u2192 1980s", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Electronic_organizer"}
{"title_page": "Queenstown Events Centre", "text_new": "{{Use dmy dates|date=November 2015}}\n{{Use New Zealand English|date=November 2015}}\n\n{{Infobox venue\n| stadium_name      = Queenstown Events Centre\n| nickname          =\n| image             = Queenstown-Events-Centre.jpg\n| image_caption     = View of the Queenstown Events Centre Building\n| location          = Joe O'connell Drive, Frankton, [[Queenstown, New Zealand|Queenstown]], [[New Zealand]]\n| coordinates       = {{Coord|45|0|58|S|168|44|18|E|display=inline,title}}\n| pushpin_map       = New Zealand transparent\n| broke_ground      =\n| opening           = \n| closed            = \n| demolished        = \n| owner             = [[Queenstown-Lakes District|Queenstown-Lakes District Council]]\n| operator          = Lakes Leisure\n| surface           = Grass\n| construction_cost = \n| architect         = \n| former_names      = John Davies Oval, Davies Park\n| tenants           = [[Otago Rugby Football Union]], [[Highlanders (rugby)|Highlanders]], [[Otago United]], [[Otago Volts]]\n| seating_capacity  = 19,000<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.icc-cricket.com/news/548142|title=U19 Venue Feature: John Davies Oval|work=International Cricket Council|accessdate=15 December 2017}}</ref>\n| embedded          =\n{{Infobox sports complex\n| embed             = yes\n| name              = Complex information\n| main_venue        = Queenstown Events Centre Building\n| other_facilities  = Alpine Aqualand, Frankton Golf Centre, Rockatipu Climbing Wall\n| opened            = 1997\n| public_transit    = Frankton Bus Interchange\n|embedded =\n{{Infobox cricket ground\n| embed            = yes\n| end1             = Remarkables End\n| end2             = Coronet Peak End\n| international    = true\n| firsttestdate    = \n| firsttestyear    = \n| firsttesthome    = \n| firsttestaway    = \n| lasttestdate     = \n| lasttestyear     = \n| lasttesthome     = \n| lasttestaway     = \n| onlytestdate     = \n| onlytestyear     = \n| onlytesthome     =  \n| onlytestaway     = \n| firstodidate     = 4 January \n| firstodiyear     = 2003\n| firstodihome     = New Zealand\n| firstodiaway     = India\n| lastodidate      = 1 January \n| lastodiyear      = 2014\n| lastodihome      = New Zealand\n| lastodiaway      = West Indies\n| firstt20idate    = \n| firstt20iyear    = \n| firstt20ihome    = \n| firstt20iaway    = \n| lastt20idate     = \n| lastt20iyear     = \n| lastt20ihome     = \n| lastt20iaway     = \n| onlyt20idate     = \n| onlyt20iyear     = \n| onlyt20ihome     =  \n| onlyt20iaway     =\n| year1            = \n| club1            =\n| date             = 8 January\n| year             = 2016\n| source           = http://www.espncricinfo.com/SriLanka/content/ground/58919.html ESPNcricinfo\n}}\n}}\n}}\n\n'''Queenstown Events Centre''', '''John Davies Oval''', or '''Davies Park''' is a multi-purpose sports complex and stadium located in [[Queenstown, New Zealand|Queenstown]], [[Otago]] in the [[South Island]] of [[New Zealand]].\n\n== History ==\n\nOpened in 1997, the venue is located on [[Queenstown Lakes District Council]]\u2013owned land and is a multi-purpose indoor and outdoor venue. The Stadium has a capacity of 19,000 spectators with 6,000 permanent seating and normally 13,000 temporary called in.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.austadiums.com/stadiums/stadiums.php?id=343|title=Queenstown Events Centre (NZ)|accessdate=9 April 2014|publisher=Austadiums}}</ref>\n\nRegarded as one of the most spectacular international cricket venues in the world, the ground is located between the foot of the [[Remarkables]] and the shores of [[Lake Wakatipu]] with Queenstown International Airport's Runway threshold nearby affording amazing views of large aircraft taking off and landing. The venue hosts regular international cricket matches, [[Highlanders (rugby)|Highlanders]] rugby games,<ref>{{cite web |title=Highlanders rugby playing ground|url= http://www.superxv.com/Highlanders/stadium.asp |publisher=\u00a9Superxv.com|accessdate=3 November 2012}}</ref> trade shows, exhibitions, seminars and concerts. It is also a \"home ground\" for Otago Cricket.\n\nOn 1 January 2014, at the Queenstown Events Centre New Zealand [[Black Caps]]' [[Corey Anderson]] broke [[Shahid Afridi]]'s 17-year-old record of the fastest One Day International (ODI) hundred by one ball, scoring his in 36 balls. He eventually ended with an unbeaten 131 that featured 14 sixes and 6 fours <ref name=\"ABC Grandstand - 1 January 2014 - Corey Anderson smashes ODI world record bringing up century against West Indies in 36 balls\">{{cite news|url=http://www.abc.net.au/news/2014-01-01/anderson-smashes-odi-century-record/5181234|title=Corey Anderson smashes ODI world record bringing up century against West Indies in 36 balls|date=1 January 2014|work=[[ABC Grandstand]]|publisher=[[Australian Broadcasting Corporation]]|accessdate=1 January 2014}}</ref> Along with Jesse Ryder, he helped New Zealand set the team record for the most sixes in an ODI innings.\n\n== Activities==\nThe Queenstown Events Centre offers many different activities, including [[#Cricket at the Queenstown Events Centre|cricket]], [[Rugby union|rugby]], [[swimming]], [[golf]], fitness training, [[tennis]] (indoor and outdoor), [[netball]] (indoor and outdoor), and [[Indoor Rock Climbing|indoor rock climbing]].<ref>{{cite web |title=Activities list|url= http://www.lakesleisure.co.nz/venue/queenstown_events_centre.html |publisher=Lakes Leisure|accessdate=3 November 2012}}</ref> The crentre is also home to several different sport clubs.\n\n=== Cricket ===\n\nA range of formats of the game of Cricket are played at the centre including, One Day Internationals, local [[Twenty20]] competitions, school cricket, and six-a-side competitions. There are also practice nets near the entrance of the centre.\n\n=== Alpine Aqualand ===\nThe Alpine Aqualand is an [[indoor water park]] located to the north of the Queenstown Events Centre stadium. The building has a 25-metre lap pool with 8 lanes, a leisure pool and [[lazy river]], two [[hydroslide]]s, a toddler pool, learners pools, and hot tubs.\n\n=== Frankton Golf Centre ===\nThe Frankton Golf Centre is a 9-hole golf course located to the south of the Queenstown Events Centre. The course has a par of 30 with 6 par 3s ranging from 73 metres to 185 metres and 3 par 4s ranging from 280 metres to 310 metres. The current record for the course is 26. The course also has a [[driving range]], a [[footgolf]] course, and a [[pro shop]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.qldc.govt.nz/recreation/golf|title=Golf|last=|first=|date=|website=www.qldc.govt.nz|language=en-US|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=2020-03-01}}</ref>\n\n=== Rockatipu Climbing Wall ===\nThe Rockatipu Climbing Wall is an indoor rock climbing wall located within the Queenstown Events Centre. It offers over 40 climbs, vertical and overhanging rock features, classes, kids' climbing courses, and equipment hire.<ref>https://www.qldc.govt.nz/recreation/climb</ref>\n\n==International centuries==\nTwo ODI centuries have been achieved at the ground.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://stats.espncricinfo.com/ci/engine/stats/index.html?class=2;filter=advanced;ground=1653;orderby=start;runsmin1=100;runsval1=runs;size=200;template=results;type=batting;view=innings|title=Statistics / Statsguru / One-Day Internationals / Batting records|accessdate=26 December 2016}}</ref> Corey Anderson scored century in 36 ball which was fastest ODI century record, later broken by AB de Villers.\n\n{| class=\"wikitable sortable\" style=\"font-size:95%\"\n! No. !! Score !! Player !! Team !! Balls !! Inns. !! Opposing team !! Date !! Result\n|-\n| 1 || 104 || [[Jesse Ryder]] || {{cr|NZ}} || {{ntsh|51}} 51 || 1 || {{cr|WIN}} || {{dts|format=dmy|2014|January|1}} || Won\n|-\n| 2 || 131* || [[Corey Anderson]] || {{cr|NZ}} || {{ntsh|47}} 47 || 1 || {{cr|WIN}} || {{dts|format=dmy|2014|January|1}} || Won\n|}\n\n==International Five-Wicket Haul